snippet.textDisplay: This song is so beautiful. Like when I first heard it, it sent chills through my body, and I still get those same chills whenever I hear it. It's crazy that music can have that sort of effect on people. My girlfriend introduced me to Harry Style's a while ago, and over the last couple of years, I've been really enjoying the solo stuff that he's been putting out. I'm a solo musician too, trying to start from nothing and make it just like him. He's one of my biggest inspirations right now, I just love his vibe and his message and it makes me feel like my dreams are achievable ❤ I've covered a few of his songs on my channel, and most recently I did a cover of "Adore You." I think it's one of the best sounding pieces of music I've ever put out. I also want to cover "Falling" at some point since it's such a good song, but I'm afraid that I wouldn't do it justice :/ I'd really appreciate if some of you guys checked out my cover. I'm just a kid with a dream, so I thought it would be worth it to ask. If you don't want to I totally get it. But for those of you who do give me a chance, thank you so much. I hope you like what you hear ❤

snippet.textDisplay:
Two things:

Firstly, Harry Styles’ music video is art, not because of the Gucci labelled chiffon blouse, and neither is it because of the Neoclassical themed interior architecture that signifies abandoned opulence.

Harry styles himself is beautiful as a person but he is not afraid to show his face of anguish and anger. He and the MV were not awkward when it showed a Gucci piece all soaking wet. The production design was not afraid of luxurious furniture bobbing up and down, and later on drowning helplessly in deep waters. It was still somehow considerate when the gush of waters flowed slowly at first from the wailing body of the piano. The attempt was neither purposelessly nonchalant nor irreverent.

It is because of its elegant portrayal of the terrifying act of emotional suicide that makes this music video, art.

It is through the destruction of decadence that lay the meaning of the lyrics “What am i now?” Because nothing is as great as an equalizer other than heartbreak. And all that this may leave you is a blouse, of whatever brand, soaking bloody wet.


Second point, here’s the thing: could it be that the first scene is the end of a previous drowning? The lyrics goes “I’m falling again; I’m falling again; I’m falling,” which repeated itself incessantly.

He knows that every time he sits down by the piano, hits the first note, and sings, that he will drown. This is a prelude to a subsequent asphyxiation, and a display of masochism - that is less grand in scale but as similar in depth as with the usual breakup and the daily heartache. This is to say an opening, closing, and reopening of wounds once recalled and relished.

To this effect, nothing better gracefully executes the terrifying territory of emotional suicide than music’s last song syndrome - the repetitive recourse of emotive purging which seldom times borderlines as obsessive compulsive.

Because as Harry Styles drowns himself, so do we also realize how we can start our own emotive purging, yet again, through song.

Because as Harry Styles drowns himself, so do we also realize  how we can start our own emotive purging, yet again, through song.
